Why Jerome Powell Must Go
NEW YORK – US President Joe Biden faces a critical decision: Who should he appoint as the head of the US Federal Reserve – thus to possibly the most powerful position within the world economy?
A wrong decision here could have grave consequences.
Under Alan Greenspan and Ben Bernanke, the Fed failed to regulate the banking system appropriately, paving the way for the worst worldwide economic downturn in 75 years.
This crisis and the political decision-makers' response to it had far-reaching political consequences; it exacerbated inequality and fostered a lasting sense of dissatisfaction among those who lost their homes and jobs.
Es gibt eine Vielzahl von Klischees, warum der derzeitige Notenbankchef Jerome Powell im Amt bestätigt werden sollte.
Es wäre ein Beweis der Überparteilichkeit.
Es würde die Glaubwürdigkeit der Fed stärken.
Gebraucht würde jemand mit Erfahrung, der uns durch die Erholung im Gefolge der Pandemie führt.
Und so weiter.
Exactly the same arguments I heard 25 years ago when I was chairman of President Bill Clinton's economic advisory board and the confirmation of Greenspan was an issue.
They were enough to convince Clinton, and the country paid a heavy price for his decision.
Ironically, President Ronald Reagan paid little heed to these arguments when he effectively fired Paul Volcker in 1987 and refused him a second term after Volcker had tamed inflation.
Reagan owed much to Volcker but sought deregulation and therefore chose Greenspan, an Ayn Rand adherent.
In economic policy, careful evaluation and sensitivity to goal conflicts are required.
How important is inflation compared to jobs and growth?
How confident can we be that markets alone will be efficient, stable, fair, and competitive?
How concerned should we be about inequality?
The two major parties in the USA have always had clearly articulated but markedly different views on these issues (at least until the Republicans succumbed to populism).
In my view, the Democrats are rightly concerned about the consequences of unemployment.
The crisis of 2008 showed that unregulated markets are neither efficient nor stable.
Beyond that, we know that traditionally marginalized groups enter the economy only under tight labor market conditions, and wage differences are reduced.
The coming years will be a test for any US central banker.
Already now, the US is facing difficult decisions regarding what to do against inflation.
Are the recent price increases essentially minor issues arising from an unprecedented economic shutdown?
How should the Fed consider the unemployment rate of African Americans, who have not yet regained their pre-pandemic standing?
Would interest rate hikes (and consequently higher unemployment) be worse than the disease itself?
Equally important: While mispricing with mortgage-backed securities played a central role in the 2008 crisis, there are now indications of even more widespread and pervasive mispricing with climate-related assets.
What should the Fed do about this?
Powell is not the man for the job.
Initially, he supported the deregulatory agenda of former President Donald Trump and thereby endangered the financial health of our world.
And even now, he hesitates to take action on climate risk, despite other central bankers around the world already declaring this to be the central problem of the coming decades.
Powell would argue that climate questions do not fall within the mandate of the Fed, but he would be wrong.
It is part of the Fed's mandate to ensure financial stability, and there is no greater threat to financial stability than climate change.
The Fed is also responsible for approving financial sector mergers, and Powell's track record suggests that he has never seen a bad merger.
A such laxity is the last thing the economy needs right now.
An acute competition failure and the lack of sufficient regulation already allow excessive profits, reduce lending to small businesses, and give dominant players more room to exploit others.
Some commentators praise Powell for the Fed's reaction to the pandemic.
But any second-year student would know that you cannot tighten monetary policy and raise interest rates during a recession.
And as Simon Johnson from MIT argues, Powell does not feel particularly committed to full employment.
On the contrary: Powell's record as a member of the US Federal Reserve Board regarding monetary tightening over the past decade was characterized by a series of misjudgments that go back to the "Taper Tantrum" of 2013.
While many observers of the Fed insist that inequality is not the bank's concern, it is a fact that the bank's policies have significant distributional effects that cannot be ignored.
Just as an early increase in interest rates can stifle growth, weak enforcement of the Community Reinvestment Act allows for greater concentrations of market power.
Finally, the recent scandal involving stock trading by leading Fed officials has undermined trust in the leadership of the central bank.
Powell's apparent lack of awareness of interest conflicts, including in managing some Fed programs in response to the pandemic, has long worried me.
Nachdem vier Jahre Trump das Vertrauen in die US-Institutionen bereits geschwächt haben, besteht nun ein echtes Risiko, dass das Vertrauen in die Integrität der Notenbank weiter leidet.
Kein Fed-Vertreter sollte einen Ethikbeauftragten brauchen, der entscheidet, wann bestimmte Börsengeschäfte unziemlich erscheinen würden.
Die Fed ähnelt in gewisser Hinsicht dem US Supreme Court.
Dieser soll über der Politik stehen, doch spätestens seit Bush v. Gore wissen wir, dass das nicht der Fall ist.
Trump hat das für alle klargestellt, die noch Zweifel hatten.
Auch die Fed soll angeblich unabhängig sein, jedoch haben Powell und Greenspan, indem sie der Deregulierungsagenda ihrer Partei folgten, klar gezeigt, dass das ebenfalls nicht zutrifft.
Doch während der Notenbankrat wichtige Entscheidungen trifft, die alle Aspekte der Wirtschaft beeinflussen, konzentriert sich die Macht traditionell in den Händen des Notenbankchefs – und zwar viel stärker als beim Gerichtsvorsitzenden des Supreme Court.
Es ist der Notenbankchef, der entscheidet, was zur Abstimmung kommt und welche Themen zurückgestellt oder forciert werden.
Die Klimafrage ist nur ein Beispiel, wo enorm wichtig ist, wer an der Spitze des Tisches sitzt.
Die USA brauchen eine Notenbank, die sich wirklich dazu bekennt, für einen stabilen, fairen, effizienten und wettbewerbsbestimmten Finanzsektor zu sorgen.
Who believes that we can rely on unregulated markets or that regulation has gone too far already, lacks insight.
We need neither an ideologue like Greenspan nor a Wall Street-friendly lawyer like Powell.
What is needed is someone who has deep economic understanding and shares Biden's values and concerns about inflation and employment.
There are certainly many people who meet these criteria.
But Biden doesn't need to look far to find someone whose abilities he has already demonstrated.
Lael Brainard is already on the Fed board, where she has shown her competence and won market confidence – without compromising on her values.
Biden can have both: a Fed chair who ensures continuity and does not unsettle the markets, but who also shares his economic and social program.
